                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360229-name-1168" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360229-name-1168" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360229-name-1168" type="surname" value="CAULTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360229-name-1168" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CAULTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Robert Ritchee and Robert Boyd. on the 20th of February, I was serving in the shop, and a boy gave me information—I pulled the prisoner's cloak aside, and found this bacon</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183602290208"></xptr>
               <p>under her apron—she said she bought it is King David-land—I went to two or three places—at last she took me into a shop, and said she bought it there—the man denied it, and said be never cut bacon in that may—I cut it sloping from the bough, which is what very few people de—I never saw it done—I can swear I put it in the window—I cut it myself—the prisoner said she bought it, and gave 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for it—the man denied it—I called the policeman in and gave her in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. I went to the cheesemonger's and bought that bacon—I then went to the prosecutor, and there I bought butter and cheese—I called there with the piece of bacon in my apron, and one little chap said, "Where is the leg of park?" he said. "I don't know"—they came to me and said, "What is that?"—I said, "I have only a bit of bacon"—and they said it was like theirs—I bought it in Back-lane, Cable-street—there was another piece cut like this in the window.</p>
